---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Platform | BeaconGuard AI Policy and Evidence Boundary"
  description="BeaconGuard sits between regulated systems and AI/model endpoints to evaluate requests against deterministic policy before execution and preserve evidence for review."
>
  <section>
    <h1>Platform</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard sits between regulated systems and AI/model endpoints. Each request is evaluated against deterministic policy before execution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What BeaconGuard Is</h2>
    <p>
      It is a runtime policy and evidence boundary that evaluates request context against centralized policy and returns an explicit decision: allow, deny, or needs review.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every decision can produce an evidence record for audit, compliance, privacy, and risk review.
    </p>
    <p>
      Related context: <a href="/deployment">Deployment</a> and <a href="/trust-assurance">Trust Center</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Where Policy Control Executes</h2>
    <div class="flow-diagram flow-diagram--sequence-4 platform-control-flow">
      <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform">
        <p class="flow-step-title">Application or workflow request</p>
        <p>Enterprise application, internal tool, or operational system sends request context.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform">
        <p class="flow-step-title">BeaconGuard policy evaluation</p>
        <p>User, role, workflow, data type, risk level, and requested action are checked.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform">
        <p class="flow-step-title">Decision response</p>
        <p>BeaconGuard returns allow, deny, or needs-review with policy reasons.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform">
        <p class="flow-step-title">Allowed execution and evidence</p>
        <p>AI/model endpoint is invoked only if allowed, with a review path and evidence record available.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Compatibility layer for non-native clients</h2>
    <p>
      Some applications do not natively emit the request structure BeaconGuard evaluates.
      In those cases, a governed compatibility layer can normalize requests before they enter the BeaconGuard control boundary.
    </p>
    <p>
      The compatibility layer does not make policy decisions.
      It does not bypass BeaconGuard.
      BeaconGuard remains the policy authority, fail-closed boundary, and evidence-emitting control layer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What BeaconGuard Is Not</h2>
    <p>BeaconGuard is not:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A chatbot or assistant.</li>
      <li>An AI model host or training platform.</li>
      <li>A prompt-engineering framework.</li>
      <li>General-purpose monitoring or observability alone.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Core Platform Functions</h2>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Policy Control Plane</h3>
        <p>Distributes signed policy artifacts and policy identity to enforcement points.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Deterministic Enforcement</h3>
        <p>Applies policy consistently across time, environments, and request variations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Evidence Emission</h3>
        <p>Records audit-ready outcomes and decision context for governance review.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Review Replay</h3>
        <p>Reconstructs historical decisions from policy state and request inputs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Applicable workflow examples</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard is designed for regulated applications, enterprise applications, internal tools, and operational systems where sensitive requests require policy evaluation before model invocation or automation.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>PHI redaction or approval before AI summarization</li>
      <li>Financial dispute review before model-assisted recommendation</li>
      <li>Internal operations automation requiring approval before action</li>
      <li>Vendor AI access requests requiring policy checks</li>
      <li>Sensitive data handling before model invocation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Failure handling</h2>
    <p>
      If trust assumptions, policy conditions, or request context are missing, malformed, or out of bounds, BeaconGuard fails closed before the request proceeds into the model or automation path.
    </p>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard governs whether AI interactions are allowed to proceed under policy at the request boundary. It does not claim to eliminate downstream workflow, policy-authoring, signer, legal, clinical, or model-quality risk.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Deep Technical Paths</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/overview">Platform overview</a></li>
      <li><a href="/docs/architecture">System architecture</a></li>
      <li><a href="/docs/policy-model">Policy model</a></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/how-it-works">See runtime workflow</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/canonical-workflow">Explore workflow examples</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/contact">Talk to a platform specialist</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    @media (max-width: 900px) {
      .platform-control-flow {
        display: block;
        gap: 0;
        width: 100%;
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-step {
        width: 100%;
        min-height: 0;
        padding: 0.9rem 0.95rem;
        border-radius: 0.65rem;
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-arrow {
        display: none !important;
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-step + .flow-step {
        margin-top: 1rem;
        position: relative;
        padding-top: 1.1rem;
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::before {
        content: "";
        position: absolute;
        left: 1rem;
        top: 0;
        width: 2px;
        height: 0.9rem;
        background: var(--brand-accent);
        transform: translateY(-65%);
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-step + .flow-step::after {
        content: "↓";
        position: absolute;
        left: 1rem;
        top: 0;
        transform: translate(-45%, -100%);
        font-size: 0.9rem;
        font-weight: 700;
        line-height: 1;
        color: var(--brand-accent);
      }

      .platform-control-flow .flow-step-title {
        margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
      }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
